not just promote like

00:44:41.540 --> 00:44:43.980
no meat, less meat.

00:44:43.980 --> 00:44:44.660
And tell me your name.

00:44:44.660 --> 00:44:45.190
BRIAN: Brian.

00:44:45.190 --> 00:44:47.430
AARON GROSS: Brian is absolutely
correct that

00:44:47.430 --> 00:44:50.910
there's no way around eating
less meat as a population.

00:44:50.910 --> 00:44:52.640
And one way to accomplish
that is a lot more

00:44:52.640 --> 00:44:53.620
vegetarians and vegans.

00:44:53.620 --> 00:44:55.950
There's really no scenario,
whether factory farming stays

00:44:55.950 --> 00:44:56.770
with us or not.

00:44:56.770 --> 00:44:58.140
So that's absolutely correct.

00:44:58.140 --> 00:44:59.750
And I do encourage people
to be vegetarian.

00:44:59.750 --> 00:45:01.710
I would encourage people
to go vegan.

00:45:01.710 --> 00:45:05.750
There's very few ways you can
have as much impact on animals

00:45:05.750 --> 00:45:07.860
and the environment than simply
just by removing them

00:45:07.860 --> 00:45:10.900
from your diet entirely because
it's extremely hard to

00:45:10.900 --> 00:45:12.380
find the really good
producers.

00:45:12.380 --> 00:45:15.660
So that is something
I would advocate.

00:45:15.660 --> 00:45:19.670
But what we see is that meat
eating is very entrenched.

00:45:19.670 --> 00:45:22.220
It's probably not gonna go
anywhere, no matter how much

00:45:22.220 --> 00:45:23.800
the vegetarian movement grows.

00:45:23.800 --> 00:45:26.690
And it is growing, and I think
it will continue to.

00:45:26.690 --> 00:45:31.240
And so what I focused on today
really was about how to make a

00:45:31.240 --> 00:45:34.640
future in which meat is still
there but has to be a smaller

00:45:34.640 --> 00:45:37.120
part of the plate, possible.

00:45:37.120 --> 00:45:37.570
BRIAN: Fair enough.

00:45:37.570 --> 00:45:39.420
And I think that makes sense.

00:45:39.420 --> 00:45:44.740
I mean I would pose sort of a
counter argument which is that

00:45:44.740 --> 00:45:47.190
I see round other than San
Francisco, and a lot of my

00:45:47.190 --> 00:45:50.930
friends they hear, oh, you're
vegan, you're vegetarian.

00:45:50.930 --> 00:45:52.370
Oh, I buy my eggs here.

00:45:52.370 --> 00:45:54.050
I'm really careful and
stuff like that.

00:45:54.050 --> 00:45:57.290
And then we're out late night in
the Mission at a taqueria,

00:45:57.290 --> 00:45:58.990
and they're having beef tacos.

00:45:58.990 --> 00:45:59.620
And guess what?

00:45:59.620 --> 00:46:02.220
Like that taqueria in the
Mission isn't buying

00:46:02.220 --> 00:46:03.910
free-range beef.

00:46:03.910 --> 00:46:07.970
And so what I've seen is that
it becomes almost more of an

00:46:07.970 --> 00:46:10.830
excuse for people to kind of
go on with their existing

00:46:10.830 --> 00:46:16.610
habits of eating meat because
they're lured into this sense

00:46:16.610 --> 00:46:19.840
of, oh yeah, I'm making a
conscious choice and I've

00:46:19.840 --> 00:46:20.930
thought about it or whatever.

00:46:20.930 --> 00:46:23.490
But they're really
kind of not.

00:46:23.490 --> 00:46:26.240
And in a sense, the people
who are the most

00:46:26.240 --> 00:46:28.100
receptive to change--

00:46:28.100 --> 00:46:30.420
like people like us, people who
are affluent, people who

00:46:30.420 --> 00:46:33.960
are well educated, people who
are open minded and willing to

00:46:33.960 --> 00:46:35.130
make the change--

00:46:35.130 --> 00:46:39.710
are kind of siphoned off when
they have options like this.

00:46:39.710 --> 00:46:41.070
AARON GROSS: So this
is, yeah--

00:46:41.070 --> 00:46:43.530
you're presenting a very serious
argument that we

00:46:43.530 --> 00:46:44.830
thought a lot about.

00:46:44.830 --> 00:46:46.910
And what I would say
is I'm sympathetic

00:46:46.910 --> 00:46:48.190
to what you're saying.

00:46:48.190 --> 00:46:50.950
I'm making a bet on a
different strategy.

00:46:50.950 --> 00:46:54.680
My observation is that
vegetarianism and lower meat

00:46:54.680 --> 00:46:58.530
or higher ethical meat diets
rise and fall together.

00:46:58.530 --> 00:47:01.520
So I see a lot of evidence that
if we get people eating

00:47:01.520 --> 00:47:05.680
higher welfare meat that we'll
also encourage vegetarianism,

00:47:05.680 --> 00:47:07.790
rather than the competitive
scenario.

00:47:07.790 --> 00:47:09.650
And I think we actually need
to do some research.

00:47:09.650 --> 00:47:11.210
This is really what I came to.

00:47:11.210 --> 00:47:13.240
Because what I want to say is
I think there are large

00:47:13.240 --> 00:47:16.370
elements of the so-called kind
of ethical or humane meat

00:47:16.370 --> 00:47:19.420
movement which are actually
really hostile to vegetarian.

00:47:19.420 --> 00:47:21.010
They don't say that
explicitly.

00:47:21.010 --> 00:47:24.180
But there's this notion that's
really kind of a meat advocacy

00:47:24.180 --> 00:47:26.470
and then do it right
on the back end.

00:47:26.470 --> 00:47:29.180
And I think that's a really
serious thing to avoid.

00:47:29.180 --> 00:47:32.700
We think it's really important
to say as we work towards

00:47:32.700 --> 00:47:36.330
higher welfare animal farms that
there is another viable

00:47:36.330 --> 00:47:38.790
option and that many people
really need to be adopting it

00:47:38.790 --> 00:47:40.420
if we're gonna be successful,
which is

00:47:40.420 --> 00:47:42.660
vegetarianism or veganism.

00:47:42.660 --> 00:47:45.270
So I don't take that as a small
part of the solution.

00:47:45.270 --> 00:47:47.030
I think it's a big part.

00:47:47.030 --> 00:47:50.860
But my bet is that we can work
for these high-welfare farms

00:47:50.860 --> 00:47:52.780
and advance that at
the same time.

00:47:52.780 --> 00:47:55.330
But I think the real answer is
we need to do some studies

00:47:55.330 --> 00:47:56.960
because this is a really
serious question.

00:47:56.960 --> 00:47:59.680
And we need to find out when we
promote this kind of thing,

00:47:59.680 --> 00:48:02.340
does it make vegetarians go back
to eating higher welfare

00:48:02.340 --> 00:48:05.820
meat or does it in fact promote
higher welfare,

00:48:05.820 --> 00:48:07.920
high-ethical eating
in general.

00:48:07.920 --> 00:48:08.250
BRIAN: Cool.

00:48:08.250 --> 00:48:09.400
Thanks for the answer.

00:48:09.400 --> 00:48:10.760
AARON GROSS: Thank you.

00:48:10.760 --> 00:48:14.440
AUDIENCE: I talked a lot of
farmers who do like the whole

00:48:14.440 --> 00:48:15.710
small farm thing.

00:48:15.710 --> 00:48:17.370
And they have problems
with the USDA.

00:48:17.370 --> 00:48:21.600
I was wondering if you're
addressing that discrimination

00:48:21.600 --> 00:48:24.920
between the factory farms
and the smaller farmers?

00:48:24.920 --> 00:48:25.340
AARON GROSS: Yeah.

00:48:25.340 --> 00:48:25.710
Absolutely.

00:48:25.710 --> 00:48:27.970
So the question is about
addressing the way in which

00:48:27.970 --> 00:48:31.160
the USDA is often a kind of
problem for small farmers.

00:48:31.160 --> 00:48:34.390
So the USDA is structured in
such a way that it really

00:48:34.390 --> 00:48:35.810
supports factory farming.

00:48:35.810 --> 00:48:37.430
They don't really know
what to do with small

00:48:37.430 --> 00:48:38.740
farmers like Frank.

00:48:38.740 --> 00:48:41.206
So the USDA comes
to Frank's farm.

00:48:41.206 --> 00:48:43.600
They're like, where are your
waste lagoons, like the big

00:48:43.600 --> 00:48:44.770
cesspool you saw there?

00:48:44.770 --> 00:48:45.940
And he's like, I don't have
any waste lagoons.

00:48:45.940 --> 00:48:46.905
Like, but you're a chicken
operation.

00:48:46.905 --> 00:48:48.240
And they literally don't
know what to do.

00:48:48.240 --> 00:48:50.230
They don't even have like
a check box for how to

00:48:50.230 --> 00:48:51.950
investigate a farm like that.

00:48:51.950 --> 00:48:53.820
And that wasn't a
problem per se.

00:48:53.820 --> 00:48:56.770
But of course in other cases,
they really do create all

00:48:56.770 --> 00:48:58.410
sorts of problems.

00:48:58.410 --> 00:48:59.830
It is something we're
working on.

00:48:59.830 --> 00:49:02.280
We've mostly found that what
these small farmers need is

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:04.510
kind of business or consulting
services.

00:49:04.510 --> 00:49:05.450
They know how to farm.

00:49:05.450 --> 00:49:06.630
They know how to produce
a product.

00:49:06.630 --> 00:49:07.700
But they don't know how to deal

00:49:07.700 --> 00:49:09.100
with government paperwork.

00:49:09.100 --> 00:49:11.470
They don't know how to put
together a business plan.

00:49:11.470 --> 00:49:14.020
They don't know how to
think in those ways.

00:49:14.020 --> 00:49:16.720
And so those are the services
we've really been providing,

00:49:16.720 --> 00:49:17.640
not just to Frank but to

00:49:17.640 --> 00:49:19.870
Kansas-area farmers in general.

00:49:19.870 --> 00:49:23.180
And as we develop this model and
as we have more resources,

00:49:23.180 --> 00:49:26.610
the idea is precisely to make
those services available.

00:49:26.610 --> 00:49:28.740
AUDIENCE: Thank you for the
talk and for your time.

00:49:28.740 --> 00:49:31.810
What are the major factors that
keep high-welfare farms

00:49:31.810 --> 00:49:34.720
from being cost competitive
with the factory farms?

00:49:34.720 --> 00:49:37.970
You mentioned that there was
more losses in terms of

00:49:37.970 --> 00:49:41.360
animals dying if they're
outside?

00:49:41.360 --> 00:49:42.680
And is it more labor
intensive?

00:49:42.680 --> 00:49:45.750
And can automation drive
that cost down?

00:49:45.750 --> 00:49:46.950
AARON GROSS: Yeah.

00:49:46.950 --> 00:49:50.090
So the question is what are
the main factors that make

00:49:50.090 --> 00:49:52.700
high-welfare farming
more expensive than

00:49:52.700 --> 00:49:53.680
lower welfare farming?

00:49:53.680 --> 00:49:57.030
Just to first clarify what I
said before, if we stick with

00:49:57.030 --> 00:49:59.610
the factory chicken genetics
and we put those birds

00:49:59.610 --> 00:50:01.640
outside, it creates
that problem.

00:50:01.640 --> 00:50:03.880
Of course, if we take
traditional birds and we raise

00:50:03.880 --> 00:50:06.030
them outside, they're
phenomenally healthy and have

00:50:06.030 --> 00:50:08.720
robust immune system.

00:50:08.720 --> 00:50:09.610
There's two issues.

00:50:09.610 --> 00:50:11.220
There's one of scale.

00:50:11.220 --> 00:50:14.400
What Frank is doing right now
is expensive in part just

00:50:14.400 --> 00:50:15.820
because he's so small.

00:50:15.820 --> 00:50:18.020
If we can scale that up
by demonstrating the

00:50:18.020 --> 00:50:20.200
effectiveness of this model,
the costs will

00:50:20.200 --> 00:50:21.920
go down to an extent.

00:50:21.920 --> 00:50:24.310
The other factor is
externalities.

00:50:24.310 --> 00:50:26.540
You currently have a factory
farm industry which can cause

00:50:26.540 --> 00:50:28.930
hundreds of millions of dollars
worth of pollution,

00:50:28.930 --> 00:50:33.520
create all sorts of injury
issues for their workers and

00:50:33.520 --> 00:50:34.120
not pay them.

00:50:34.120 --> 00:50:36.890
So you've got all of these
externalized costs that aren't

00:50:36.890 --> 00:50:40.670
externalized in the
high-welfare farm.

00:50:40.670 --> 00:50:42.040
They are polluting something.

00:50:42.040 --> 00:50:43.110
They're cleaning it
up and so forth.

00:50:43.110 --> 00:50:44.330
They're different
kind of players.

00:50:44.330 --> 00:50:47.050
So if we can clean up the
externalities, which is a

00:50:47.050 --> 00:50:49.830
legal issue, that would
deal with the largest

00:50:49.830 --> 00:50:50.650
kind of chunk of it.

00:50:50.650 --> 00:50:53.600
And it's hard to calculate
exactly how much those things

00:50:53.600 --> 00:50:56.030
cost for the reasons
you can imagine.

00:50:56.030 --> 00:50:57.660
It's a complicated equation.

00:50:57.660 --> 00:50:59.590
But it will be more expensive.

00:50:59.590 --> 00:51:02.960
Meat is artificially
cheap right now.

00:51:02.960 --> 00:51:06.640
We pay less for food of any
kind then at any point in

00:51:06.640 --> 00:51:09.070
human history in terms of
percentage of our income.

00:51:09.070 --> 00:51:10.020
It's incredibly small.

00:51:10.020 --> 00:51:11.590
We think food's gotten a little
bit more expensive

00:51:11.590 --> 00:51:13.350
recently, but it's still
historically

00:51:13.350 --> 00:51:14.790
at an all-time low.

00:51:14.790 --> 00:51:17.170
And so part of the solution here
is to get us a little bit

00:51:17.170 --> 00:51:19.220
more comfortable spending a
larger percentage of our

00:51:19.220 --> 00:51:22.260
income, whether we're wealthy
or poor, but a larger

00:51:22.260 --> 00:51:25.640
percentage of our income on food
and probably less higher

00:51:25.640 --> 00:51:26.825
quality meat.

00:51:26.825 --> 00:51:28.290
AUDIENCE: Hi there.

00:51:28.290 --> 00:51:30.980
I used to work for a large
environmental organization.

00:51:30.980 --> 00:51:33.740
And I was always amazed that
animal agriculture really

00:51:33.740 --> 00:51:35.710
didn't make the list of things
we talked about.

00:51:35.710 --> 00:51:37.130
We talked about a lot
of other things.

00:51:37.130 --> 00:51:41.160
But as the number one cause of
climate change, I felt like we

00:51:41.160 --> 00:51:42.690
were burying our heads
in the sand when we

00:51:42.690 --> 00:51:43.700
didn't address it directly.

00:51:43.700 --> 00:51:47.400
And, I guess it's not a really
targeted question, but I would

00:51:47.400 --> 00:51:49.490
guess that if we could get the
environmental community more

00:51:49.490 --> 00:51:54.160
behind alternatives to current
animal agriculture that we'd

00:51:54.160 --> 00:51:56.400
see faster progress
potentially.

00:51:56.400 --> 00:51:58.460
Do you have thoughts on why
we haven't seen the

00:51:58.460 --> 00:52:00.040
environmental movement--

00:52:00.040 --> 00:52:03.760
is it just that vegetarianism or
eating meat is so personal

00:52:03.760 --> 00:52:04.970
that it's something they're
scared to touch?

00:52:04.970 --> 00:52:07.410
I'd just love to hear your
thoughts on that.

00:52:07.410 --> 00:52:07.630
AARON GROSS: Yeah.

00:52:07.630 --> 00:52:08.050
Thank you.

00:52:08.050 --> 00:52:08.720
No, it's a great question.

00:52:08.720 --> 00:52:11.310
So the question is why haven't
environmental groups been more

00:52:11.310 --> 00:52:13.500
active fighting factory farming
and talking about

00:52:13.500 --> 00:52:15.980
these diet issues, and yeah,
a question of longstanding

00:52:15.980 --> 00:52:16.810
interest to me.

00:52:16.810 --> 00:52:19.350
It is one of the reasons I
started the talk with talking

00:52:19.350 --> 00:52:21.850
about identity and the way in
which it's bound up because I

00:52:21.850 --> 00:52:23.990
think that's a huge
part of it.

00:52:23.990 --> 00:52:25.150
There's something--

00:52:25.150 --> 00:52:27.620
with many environmental groups,
there's history of

00:52:27.620 --> 00:52:30.140
connection with hunting and
preservation around that which

00:52:30.140 --> 00:52:31.720
has become part of
their ethos.

00:52:31.720 --> 00:52:33.300
But whether it's an
environmental group or any

00:52:33.300 --> 00:52:36.430
other kind of group, for the
most part, Americans work

00:52:36.430 --> 00:52:39.150
within a frame in which
you have to eat meat.

00:52:39.150 --> 00:52:42.220
That's not a decision that's
going to be negotiated or

00:52:42.220 --> 00:52:42.720
considered.

00:52:42.720 --> 00:52:44.480
It's kind of an unwritten law.

00:52:44.480 --> 00:52:46.600
The way you can kind of do this
as a thought experiment

00:52:46.600 --> 00:52:48.330
is could someone become
president if they were a

00:52:48.330 --> 00:52:49.920
vegetarian?

00:52:49.920 --> 00:52:52.910
There's no law against a
presidential candidate being

00:52:52.910 --> 00:52:53.450
vegetarian.

00:52:53.450 --> 00:52:55.900
But honestly, what do you think
would happen if we had a

00:52:55.900 --> 00:52:57.710
vegetarian?

00:52:57.710 --> 00:52:59.590
They'd be killed, no
pun intended here.

00:52:59.590 --> 00:53:01.630
It's just completely
unacceptable.

00:53:01.630 --> 00:53:04.450
And it's only really the animal
movement which has

00:53:04.450 --> 00:53:07.400
gotten over that cultural
barrier and is willing to say

00:53:07.400 --> 00:53:09.550
to people, you know what, maybe
you shouldn't eat them

00:53:09.550 --> 00:53:11.280
at all or you should eat less.

00:53:11.280 --> 00:53:13.400
It's happening in the
environmental movement now.

00:53:13.400 --> 00:53:15.730
A few years ago, Sierra, Club
became the first to kind of

00:53:15.730 --> 00:53:18.020
have a big campaign against
factory farms.

00:53:18.020 --> 00:53:19.500
And it does help a lot.

00:53:19.500 --> 00:53:22.420
And the Waterkeepers Alliance
won some incredible lawsuits

00:53:22.420 --> 00:53:24.960
against pig factory farms.

00:53:24.960 --> 00:53:27.020
It cost them $12 million
in lawsuits.

00:53:27.020 --> 00:53:30.430
Unfortunately the CEO of
Smithfield at the time took a

00:53:30.430 --> 00:53:31.530
$12 million bonus.

00:53:31.530 --> 00:53:33.930
So it shows you how much
that is a big fine.

00:53:33.930 --> 00:53:36.930
But the environmental groups
are having an impact.

00:53:36.930 --> 00:53:38.000
And we are seeing
progress there.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:39.820
But that's a cultural battle.

00:53:39.820 --> 00:53:42.150
And I think one of the most
important things we can do is

00:53:42.150 --> 00:53:45.300
really just to get people
comfortable talking about meat

00:53:45.300 --> 00:53:47.680
as something optional, as
something which may be if it

00:53:47.680 --> 00:53:50.420
doesn't meet our values, we
shouldn't be eating it.

00:53:50.420 --> 00:53:52.540
And if we do want to eat
it, maybe we need

00:53:52.540 --> 00:53:54.180
to change the system.

00:53:54.180 --> 00:53:56.840
And that's a tough one and
very important one.

00:53:56.840 --> 00:53:57.520
Good question.

00:53:57.520 --> 00:53:59.300
Good question to end on.

